</xrlabel><xr-g-blk><xr-g e_targeteltid="13cbac3d526.7ccc"><xh-blk><xh><a href="entry://sine qua non">sine qua non</a></xh></xh-blk></xr-g></xr-g-blk> </xr-gs></sn-g></sn-blk-nolist></sn-gs></h-g>
</>

e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a41"><body e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a42"><title e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a43" e_inline="y"><titled tranID="1" status="3">Dealing with questions<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>应对提问</chn></titled></title><p e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a45" e_inline="y"><und margined="n">If you give a talk, for example at a conference, you need to explain to the audience when they can ask questions, and deal with the questions they ask.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>在需要发言的场合，比如在会议上，需要告诉听众何时可以提问并应对提问</chn>：</und></p><ul e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a44" class="bullet"><li nobullet="y"><x-gs e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a47"><x-g-blk eid=""><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a49" e_inline="y" tranID="3" status="3"> <ebi>There will be time for questions at the end,</ebi> if you'd like to save them up till then.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>最后会有提问的时间，大家不妨等到那个时候再发问。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li nobullet="y"><x-gs e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a4c"><x-g-blk eid=""><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a4e" e_inline="y" tranID="4" status="3">If you don't mind, <ebi>we'll take all of your questions at the end of the presentation.</ebi> <chnsep> </chnsep><chn>如果诸位不介意的话，我们将在演示结束时统一回应大家的提问。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li nobullet="y"><x-gs e_id="u4cdebea65f7df6b4.-51b21c88.142be30b553.2a51"><x-g-blk eid=""><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x tranID="18" status="1">quick / quickly / fast</titled></title><ul eid="quick_ul_1" class="bullet" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d8d"><li eid="quick_li_1" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d8c" e_inline="y"><und margined="n"> <eb>Quickly</eb>  is the usual adverb from  <eb>quick</eb>.<chnsep> * </chnsep><chn>quickly 为源自 quick 的常用副词</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quick_xgs_8" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d89"><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_27"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_27" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d87" e_inline="y" tranID="3" status="6">I quickly realized that I was on the wrong train.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>我很快意识到我坐错了火车。</chn></x></x-g-blk><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_28"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_28" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d85" e_inline="y" tranID="5" status="6">My heart started to beat more quickly.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>我的心开始跳得快起来。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li eid="quick_li_2" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d84" e_inline="y"><und margined="n"> <eb>Quick</eb>  is sometimes used as an adverb in very informal language, especially as an exclamation.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>在日常用语中，quick 有时用作副词，尤作感叹语</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quick_xgs_9" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d82"><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_29"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_29" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d80" e_inline="y" tranID="7" status="6">Come on! Quick! They'll see us!<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>快点儿吧！快！他们会看见我们的！</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs><und margined="y"> <eb>Quicker</eb>  is used more often.<chnsep> * </chnsep><chn>quicker 更常用</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quick_xgs_10" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d7e"><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_30"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_30" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d7c" e_inline="y" tranID="9" status="6">My heart started to beat much quicker.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>我的心跳开始大大加快。</chn></x></x-g-blk><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_31"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_31" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d7a" e_inline="y" tranID="11" status="6">The quicker I get you away from here, the better.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>我越快送你离开此地越好。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li eid="quick_li_3" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d79" e_inline="y"><und margined="n"> <eb>Fast</eb>  is more often used when you are talking about the speed that somebody or something moves at.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>指某人或某物移动的速度多用 fast</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quick_xgs_11" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d77"><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_32"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_32" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d75" e_inline="y" tranID="13" status="6">How fast can a cheetah run?<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>猎豹奔跑的速度有多快？</chn></x></x-g-blk><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_33"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quick_x_33" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d73" e_inline="y" tranID="15" status="6">Can't you drive any faster?<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>你难道不能开快点儿？</chn></x></x-g-blk><x-g-blk eid="quick_xg_34"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><wx eid="quick_wx_1" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5d71">You're driving too quickly.</wx></x-g-blk></x-gs><und margined="y"> There is no word  <eb>fastly</eb>.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>没有 fastly 这个词。</chn></und></li></ul></body></unbox></sn-g></licontent></xhtml:li></xhtml:ol></sn-blk></sn-gs></h-g>
</>

</chnsep><chn>这场考试十分难。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li eid="quite_li_4" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5626" e_inline="y"><und margined="n"> <eb>Quite</eb>  is a little stronger than  <eb>fairly</eb>, and  <eb>rather</eb>  is a little stronger than  <eb>quite</eb>.  <eb>Rather</eb>  is not very common in <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="n_am"><xhtml:a href="helpg:am"><namelabel>NAmE</namelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g></label-g-blk>;  <eb>pretty</eb>  has the same meaning and this is used in informal <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="br"><xhtml:a href="helpg:br"><brelabel>BrE</brelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g> </label-g-blk> too.<chnsep> * </chnsep><chn>quite 比 fairly 语气稍强，而 rather 又比 quite 语气稍强。在美式英语中，rather 不太常用。pretty 与 rather 含义相同，也用于非正式英式英语</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quite_xgs_14" e_id="13cbac3027d.-561b"><x-g-blk eid="quite_xg_36"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quite_x_35" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5619" e_inline="y" <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="br"><xhtml:a href="helpg:br"><brelabel>BrE</brelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g> </label-g-blk>  <eb>quite</eb>  has two meanings.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>在英式英语中，quite 含义有二</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quite_xgs_15" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5614"><x-g-blk eid="quite_xg_37"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="quite_x_36" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5612" e_inline="y" tranID="19" status="2">I feel quite tired today<gl-blk>(= <gl>fairly tired</gl>)</gl-blk>.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>今天我感到相当累。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs><und margined="y">With adjectives that describe an extreme state ('non-gradable' adjectives) it means 'completely' or 'absolutely'.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>与表示极端状态的形容词（即非级差形容词）连用，意为完全地、绝对地</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quite_xgs_16" </chnsep><chn>我感到筋疲力尽。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs><und margined="y">With some adjectives, both meanings are possible. The speaker's stress and intonation will show you which is meant.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>与某些形容词连用，两种含义均有可能，究竟属于哪一种由说话者的重音和语调决定</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="quite_xgs_17" e_id="13cbac3027d.-560d"><x-g-blk better</gl>)</gl-blk>.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>你的文章还不错（挺好，不过可以更好）；</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs><x-gs eid="quite_xgs_18" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5609"><x-g-blk eid="quite_xg_40"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x </chnsep><chn>你的文章简直太好了（非常好，尤指出乎意料）。</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li><li eid="quite_li_6" e_id="13cbac3027d.-5605" e_inline="y"><und margined="n">In <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo <eb>Pretty</eb>  is used instead for this sense.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>在美式英语中，quite 通常为 very 之义，而非 fairly 或 rather。表示后一种意思用 pretty。</chn></und></li></ul></body></unbox></sn-g></licontent></xhtml:li></xhtml:ol></sn-blk><sn-blk shcut="n"><xhtml:ol start="4"><xhtml:li><licontent><sn-g eid="quite_sng_4" n=""><v-gs-blk quiz</a></xh></xh-blk></xr-g></xr-g-blk> </xr-gs></sn-g></licontent></xhtml:li></xhtml:ol></sn-blk><unbox type="more_about" Name="exams" eid="exam_unbox_1" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-35e"><body eid="exam_body_1" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-35d"><title eid="exam_h1_1" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-35c" e_inline="y"><titled tranID="6" status="2">exams<chnsep> </chnsep><chn/></titled></title><ul eid="exam_ul_1" class="bullet" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-35b"><li eid="exam_li_1" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-35a" e_inline="y"><und margined="n"> <eb>Exam</eb>  is the usual word for a written, spoken or practical test at school or college, especially an important one that you need to do in order to get a qualification.  <eb>Examination</eb>  is a very formal word. A  <eb>test</eb>  is something that students might be given in addition to, or sometimes instead of, regular exams, to see how much they have learned. A very short informal test is called a  <eb>quiz</eb>  in <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="n_am"><xhtml:a href="helpg:am"><namelabel>NAmE</namelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g></label-g-blk>.  <eb>Quiz</eb>  in both <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="n_am"><xhtml:a href="helpg:am"><namelabel>NAmE</namelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g> </label-g-blk> and <label-g-blk><label-g><geo-blk><geo geo="br"><xhtml:a href="helpg:br"><brelabel>BrE</brelabel></xhtml:a></geo></geo-blk></label-g> </label-g-blk> also means a contest in which people try to answer questions.<chnsep> * </chnsep><chn>exam 为常用词，指学校的笔试、口试或操作考试，尤指为取得学历必须参加的重要考试。examination 是很正式的词。test 指对学生所学知识的测验，是正规考试的补充，有时也取代正规考试。在美式英语中非正规的小测验称为 quiz；在美式英语和英式英语中 quiz 亦指问答竞赛</chn>：</und><x-gs eid="exam_xgs_3" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-34e"><x-g-blk eid="exam_xg_13"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="exam_x_13" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-34c" e_inline="y" tranID="3" status="6">a trivia quiz<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>难题问答竞赛</chn></x></x-g-blk><x-g-blk eid="exam_xg_14"><xsymb>◆</xsymb><x eid="exam_x_14" e_id="13cbabd5a4a.-34a" e_inline="y" tranID="5" status="6">a quiz show<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>问答竞赛节目</chn></x></x-g-blk></x-gs></li></ul></body></unbox></sn-gs></subentry-g></div><div id="verb" class="cixing_part"><top-g> <h e_id="13cbac3027d.-5557">quiz</h><infl margined="n">These words all mean to write or speak about sb/sth, often in order to give an example or prove sth.<chnsep> </chnsep><chn>以上各词均含写到、说到、谈及或举例说明之义。</chn></und></p><ul eid="mention_ul_2" is a more formal word than  <eb>quote</eb>  and is often used in more formal situations, for example in descriptions of legal cases.<chnsep> * </chnsep><chn>cite 较 quote 正式，常用于较正式的场合中，如说明法律案件。</chn></und></li></ul><h3 eid="mention_h3_2" e_id="13cbac01393.7595" e_inline="y" tranID="25" status="1">Patterns</h3><ul eid="mention_ul_4" class="bullet"
